  "theory": {
    "id": "b1-u38-theory",
    "title": "Learn the rule",
    "shortTitle": "Theory",
    "displayMode": "swipeable_cards",
    "completionRule": {
      "type": "view_all_cards",
      "required": true
    },
    "cards": [
      {
        "id": "theory-card-1",
        "title": "Both",
        "subtitle": "Both",
        "cardType": "rule_card",
        "sections": [
          {
            "type": "bullet_list",
            "title": "Use",
            "items": [
              "To emphasise that two things are equally true.",
              "To make the same statement about two people or things."
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "example_list",
            "title": "Examples",
            "items": [
              [
                "**Both** Sophie and James arrived early for the meeting.",
                "The exam was **both** long **and** difficult."
              ],
              [
                "My brother and I were **both** surprised by the result.",
                "Anna and Pete **both** enjoyed the concert."
              ]
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "chips",
            "title": "Useful notes",
            "items": [
              "We often use **of** with **both** before a pronoun.",
              "I used to work with Nina and Chris, but I've lost touch with **both of** them."
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "id": "theory-card-2",
        "title": "Either",
        "subtitle": "Either",
        "cardType": "rule_card",
        "sections": [
          {
            "type": "bullet_list",
            "title": "Use",
            "items": [
              "To present a choice between two options."
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "example_list",
            "title": "Examples",
            "items": [
              [
                "You can take **either** the bus **or** the train.",
                "He'll be **either** angry **or** relieved when he hears the news.",
                "You can **either** apologise now **or** explain later."
              ]
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "chips",
            "title": "Useful notes",
            "items": [
              "We often use **of** with **either** before a pronoun.",
              "I like Tom and Sam — I'd be happy going to the cinema with **either of** them."
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "id": "theory-card-3",
        "title": "Neither",
        "subtitle": "Neither",
        "cardType": "rule_card",
        "sections": [
          {
            "type": "bullet_list",
            "title": "Use",
            "items": [
              "To indicate that neither of two options applies."
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "example_list",
            "title": "Examples",
            "items": [
              [
                "She has **neither** the time **nor** the money to go on holiday.",
                "His explanation was **neither** clear **nor** helpful."
              ]
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "chips",
            "title": "Useful notes",
            "items": [
              "We often use **of** with **neither** before a pronoun.",
              "**Neither of** them remembered to bring the tickets."
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "id": "theory-card-4",
        "title": "So, nor",
        "subtitle": "So, nor",
        "cardType": "rule_card",
        "sections": [
          {
            "type": "bullet_list",
            "title": "Use",
            "items": [
              "Use **so** to add more information to a positive statement.",
              "Use **nor** to add more information to a negative statement."
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "example_list",
            "title": "Examples",
            "items": [
              [
                "Sam is very patient, and **so is** Emma.",
                "I've never been to Tokyo, and **nor has** my sister."
              ],
              [
                "He didn't understand the question, and **nor did I**.",
                "You passed the test, and **so did** your classmate."
              ]
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "chips",
            "title": "Useful notes",
            "items": [
              "We can use these structures on their own in conversation.",
              "'I prefer tea to coffee.' — 'So do I.'",
              "'I've never tried sushi.' — 'Nor have I.'"
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
